{ White has an extra bishop, but black has a pawn ready to promote, and a rook to support it. How does white save a draw? }
1. Re1 { Correct! White defends against promotion from the side, as after 1. Ra3? Ra8+ 2. Kb4 Rxa3 black promotes. } (1. Ra3 Ra8+ 2. Kb4 Rxa3) 1... Rb1 { Black goes for the most challenging response, threatening to promote to a queen and attacking the white rook. How does white continue? } (1... a1=Q+ 2. Rxa1 Ra8+ 3. Kb4 Rxa1 4. Bd4 { And white will save the draw. }) 2. Re4+ { Correct! The white rook steps out of the attack with a gain of tempo. } 2... Kf5 { Black moves aside, still threatening to promote and now attacking both the white rook and bishop. How does white continue? } 3. Ra4 { Correct! White has to stop the pawn from promoting at all costs. } 3... a1=Q { White seems to be lost, as black promotes to a queen. How does white still save a draw here? } (3... Rxg1 4. Rxa2) 4. Bd4! { Correct! White saves his bishop, and as the black queen is trapped, white will win the black queen on the next move! (1/2-1/2) } (4. Rxa1? Rxa1+ 5. Kb5 Rxg1 { And black wins. }) *


