{ In this position, the white pieces have seemingly gotten themselves into major trouble, and the black king threatens to take the rook to force a draw. How does white miraculously win this position? }
1. Nh6! { Correct! White threatens to save the rook and the win, forcing black to capture the rook. } 1... Kxh8 { Black takes the rook, and offers a draw. How do you continue? } (1... Kxh6 2. Kxe6 { And white will easily convert with an extra rook. }) 2. Kf6! { Correct! White traps the black king in the corner, leaving black no option but to move his e-pawn. } (2. Kxe6 Kg7 { If the black king is allowed to escape the corner, a draw becomes inevitable. }) 2... e5 $7 { Black runs with his e-pawn, and offers white a draw again. Do you accept? } 3. Kf7! { Correct! White plays on, having bigger plans than a draw. } (3. Nf7+? Kg8 { And black escapes. }) 3... e4 $7 { Black still has no choice but to push his e-pawn. How does white continue? } 4. Kf8 { Correct! White further increases the bind on the black king. } (4. Kf6 { Technically this also wins, but it is two moves slower. } 4... e3 5. Kf7 e2 6. Kf8 e1=Q 7. Nf7#) 4... e3 $7 { Black yet again moves his e-pawn. How does white finish the game? } 5. Nf7# { Correct! Black is mated with the lone knight and king. Although usually a knight and king do not suffice to win, this is one of the few exceptions where black was stuck in a mating net. (1-0) } (5. Kf7 { If white wants to make black suffer for his draw offers, he can even delay the mate by two moves. } 5... e2 6. Kf8 e1=Q 7. Nf7#) *


